    "This appears to be a main reason why T. Mochizuki prefers them to the actual Stokes or singular directions and builds his theory around them (see [Moc25, §1.4.5]).",
    "First of all, note that the statement makes sense since #S 0 (f) = #S 0 (g): If the highest power appearing in f is z m/n, then the highest power appearing in g is w m/(m-n).",
    "Since the Legendre transform ℓ f is a homeomorphism between two circles, it suffices to show that any point of S 0 (f) is mapped to a point of S 0 (g).",
    "Let (θ, [ f ]) ∈ S 0 (f), i.e.",
    "lim r→∞ Re f (re iθ) = 0, and denote by (θ ′, [g]) the corresponding point in the Legendre transform."
